[normal]Written evidence submitted by Channel 4 [WAS0028][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Channel 4 welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee’s inquiry into women’s sport.
[normal]We note, in particular, that the Committee has decided to focus in part on the media coverage of women’s sports. As a 
[normal]UK public service
[normal] broadcaster
[normal] that televises a select number of sporting events
[normal], Channel 4 is committed to providing coverage of women in 
[normal]sport, and our response below is confined specificall
[normal]y to this aspect of the inquiry, rather than the broader topic of women’s sport.
[normal]Channel 4’s coverage of sports has, over the years, tended to 
[normal]focus on one or two major sporting commitments, for example 
[normal]cricket from 1999 to 2005 and, latterly, through our coverage of 
[normal]disability
[normal] sport and horseracing
[normal]. In 2013, Channel 4 took over 
[normal]live coverage of all the major horseracing meetings 
[normal]in the UK
[normal].
[normal]These events are both notable for involving sports in which women
[normal] compete on an equal footing, either alongside men’s events (such as women’s athletics) or as competitors with men (for example, the Paralympic sport Boccia and in horseracing where there are an increasing number of female jockeys).
[normal] As such, while Channel 
[normal]4 does not provide as extensive levels of sports coverage as other broadcasters, our coverage of a select number of sports makes a significant contribution to the coverage of female competitors as well as men.
[normal]The following submission 
[normal]sets out Channel 4’s 
[normal]approach to coverage in this area, looking at our current range of sports programming and our plans for broadcas
[normal]ting these sports in the future, which we hope the Committee will find useful as part of their wider inquiry into women’s sport.
